    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants might be suffering from a condition known as \"chlorosis,\" which is often caused by a lack of iron in the soil. You can remedy this by adding a few drops of iron chelate to the soil, which will help the plants get the nutrients they need. It's also a good idea to check the soil pH, as tomatoes prefer slightly acidic soil. If it's too alkaline, you can add sulfur to lower the pH. Remember, just like a well-balanced diet keeps a healthy body, a well-balanced soil keeps your plants thriving. Keep an eye on them, and they'll thank you with a bountiful harvest!",
