    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tip. i think it might be nitrogen though cause the yellowing is spreading a bit. if it is a nitrogen deficiency, am i looking at something that just \"disappears\" from the soil or is something else actually eating it up? i'm trying to figure out if i just need more fertilizer or if there's some kind of hidden problem in the dirt.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nitrogen deficiency can indeed cause yellowing leaves, but it's not necessarily a disappearing act. Nitrogen can be leached away by water, especially in sandy soils, or it can be taken up by other plants, like weeds, if they're competing for the same resources. If you're suspecting nitrogen deficiency, it's wise to test your soil to confirm. If it is low in nitrogen, you can add a balanced fertilizer or specifically a nitrogen-rich one. But be cautious not to over-fertilize, as that can harm your plants and the surrounding environment. It's like a delicate dance with your garden; too much of a good thing can lead to a less-than-great outcome. Just like a well-tended garden, the right balance of nutrients will help your tomatoes flourish. Keep an eye on your plants and they'll grow strong and healthy, just like a well-fed and happy community of garden dwellers!",
      "source": "target",
